[{"id":41670,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$-2 \\mathrm{~F}$","$\\mathrm{F} / 3$","$-2 F / 3$","$-\\mathrm{F} / 3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Force between two long conductor carrying current\n$$\nF=\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi} \\frac{l_1 l_2}{d} \\ell\n$$\nAccording to question\n$$\nF^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi} \\frac{\\left(-2 I_1\\right)\\left(I_2\\right)}{d} \\ell\n$$\nFrom equation (i) and (ii), $\\mathrm{F}^{\\prime}=-\\frac{3}{2} \\mathrm{~F}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41579,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e9a905e2-1b21-4dbc-9999-7c5f378b3579-WhatsAppImage2020-12-29at1.48.45PM.jpeg\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 146px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af3c291b-cab9-4e62-87c4-8a0bf828eb86-WhatsAppImage2020-12-29at1.48.45PM(1).jpeg\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 153px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4b8388e3-b999-45b8-9b86-6c602e1a20de-WhatsAppImage2020-12-29at1.48.45PM(2).jpeg\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 145px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f84c9aec-ef36-495f-bb35-e897d20a90ff-WhatsAppImage2020-12-29at1.48.45PM(3).jpeg\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 146px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4204364d-5ef9-4f45-9c91-2bdb24eef607-image.png\" style=\"width: 462px; height: 167px;\" /></p><p>Net acceleration of particle is constant, initial velocity is zero therefore path is straight line.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cc8f7490-24c2-4a8c-b033-b959dda634b0-WhatsAppImage2020-12-29at1.53.23PM.jpeg\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 154px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41428,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$4: 5$","$16: 25$","$64: 125$","$25: 16$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RRz7Q_4AJZM3z8mNQUJMtSembhHWyK9nSvaWONjGWW4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{B}_1=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{i}}{2 \\mathrm{R}} \\qquad \\mathrm{B}_2=\\mathrm{B}_1 \\sin ^3 \\theta \\\\ & \\therefore \\frac{\\mathrm{~B}_2}{\\mathrm{~B}_1}=\\sin ^3 \\theta=\\left(\\frac{4}{5}\\right)^3=\\frac{64}{125}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41665,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["its velocity will decrease.","its velocity will increase.","it will turn towards right of direction of motion.","it will turn towards left of direction of motion"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\vec{F}=-e[\\vec{E}+\\vec{v} \\times \\vec{B}]=-e \\vec{E}$\n$\\vec{a}=-\\frac{e \\vec{E}}{m}$\n$v(t)=v_{\\circ}-\\frac{e E}{m} t$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":41419,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$\\frac{3 \\pi \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{\\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{a}}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}$","$\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{3 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}$","$\\frac{2 \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{3 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9wzWCy6E31UY5aGgvMxAac9ksiwRrUh20rlY5BnC2Zk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}=\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}_{\\mathrm{AB}}+\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}_{\\mathrm{BC}}+\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}_{\\mathrm{CD}}+\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}_{\\mathrm{DA}}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned} \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}= & {\\left[\\frac{-\\mu_0(2 \\mathrm{I} / 3)}{4 \\pi(\\mathrm{a} / 2)} \\sqrt{2}-\\frac{\\mu_0(2 \\mathrm{I} / 3)}{4 \\pi(\\mathrm{a} / 2)} \\sqrt{2}\\right.} \\\\ & \\left.+\\frac{\\mu_0(\\mathrm{I} / 3)}{4 \\pi(\\mathrm{a} / 2)} \\sqrt{2}+\\frac{\\mu_0(\\mathrm{I} / 3)}{4 \\pi(\\mathrm{a} / 2)} \\sqrt{2}\\right] \\hat{\\mathrm{k}} \\\\ \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}= & {\\left[\\frac{-2 \\sqrt{2} \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{3 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}+\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{3 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}\\right] \\hat{\\mathrm{k}} } \\\\ \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}}= & \\frac{-\\sqrt{2} \\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{3 \\pi \\mathrm{a}} \\hat{\\mathrm{k}}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41605,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The kinetic energy of a charge&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math>&nbsp;of mass&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>&nbsp;in potential is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi></msqrt></math></p><p>Then, the radius of the charge will be,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi></msqrt><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mi>q</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>Hence, the ratio of radius of proton to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>-particle,<br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math><math><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41432,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$a e^{-\\frac{4 \\pi \\mathrm{mv}_{\\mathrm{o}}}{\\mathrm{q} \\mu_{\\mathrm{o}} \\mathrm{I}}}$","$a\\left[1-\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}_{\\mathrm{o}}}{2 q \\mu_{\\mathrm{o}} \\mathrm{I}}\\right]$","$a\\left[1-\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}}{\\mathrm{q} \\mu_{\\mathrm{o}} \\mathrm{I}}\\right]$","$\\frac{a}{2}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cqVQBTTu_B8rY6gZGhZFIEatSRNwqYKFvWXGppPLEns.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & A \\rightarrow B \\\\ & \\vec{V}=-v_x \\hat{i}+v_y \\hat{j} \\\\ & \\vec{B}=\\frac{\\mu_0 I}{2 \\pi r}(-\\hat{k}) \\\\ & \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}}=\\mathrm{q}(\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}} \\times \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}})=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi r}\\left[-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\hat{\\mathrm{j}}-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{y}} \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}\\right] \\\\ & \\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{x}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\cdot \\frac{v_y}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{y}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi m} \\cdot \\frac{v_x}{\\mathrm{r}}\\end{aligned}$\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\mathrm{dr}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{y}}}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{y}}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\frac{\\mathrm{dr}}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\int_0^{\\mathrm{v}_0} \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{v}_0^2-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}}^2}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}^{\\mathrm{x}_1}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\int_{\\mathrm{a}}^{\\mathrm{dr}} \\frac{\\mathrm{r}}{2} \\\\ & \\text { Let, } \\mathrm{z}^2=\\mathrm{v}_0^2-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}}^2 \\\\ & 2 \\mathrm{zdz}=-2 \\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}\\end{aligned}$\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{zdz}=-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\\\\n& \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_x}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{v}_0^2-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}}^2}}=\\frac{-\\mathrm{zdz}}{\\mathrm{z}}=-\\mathrm{dz}\n\\end{aligned}$\nthen integral becomes\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& -\\int_{\\mathrm{v}_0}^0 \\mathrm{dz}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\ln \\frac{\\mathrm{x}_1}{\\mathrm{a}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{v}_0=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\ln \\frac{\\mathrm{x}_1}{\\mathrm{a}}\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\left.\\mathrm{x}_1=\\mathrm{a} \\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{2 \\pi \\mathrm{mv}}{\\mu_0}} \\mathrm{H}_0 \\mathrm{q} \\right\\rvert\\, \\ldots \\ldots$\n\nFor B $\\rightarrow$ C\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}}=-v_x \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}-v_y \\hat{\\mathrm{j}} \\\\\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{~B}}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}}(-\\hat{\\mathrm{k}}) \\\\\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}}=\\mathrm{q}(\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}} \\times \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}})=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi r}\\left(-v_x \\hat{j}+v_y \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}\\right)\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{x}}=+\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{y}}}{\\mathrm{r}} \\quad \\mathrm{a}_{\\mathrm{y}}=-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\cdot \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\mathrm{dr}}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{y}}}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\int_{v_0}^0 \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\mathrm{dv}_{\\mathrm{x}}}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{v}_0^2-\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{x}}^2}}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\int_{\\mathrm{x_1}}^{\\mathrm{x}}\\frac{dr}{r}\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}} \\ln \\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\mathrm{x}_1}=-\\int_0^{\\mathrm{v}_0} \\mathrm{~d} \\mathrm{z}=-\\mathrm{v}_0 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{x}=\\mathrm{x}_1 \\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{2 \\pi \\mathrm{~m}_0}{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}} \\ldots \\ldots \\text { (2) }\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nFrom equation 1 and 2\n$X=a e^{-\\frac{4 \\pi \\mathrm{mv}_0}{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{Iq}}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41571,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>I</mi><mmultiscripts><mi>a</mi><none/><mn>2</mn><mprescripts/><none/><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>I</mi><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><none/><mn>3</mn><mprescripts/><none/><mn>2</mn></mmultiscripts></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/54b78ff8-4005-43a9-9b2e-945dd8a62fef-image.png\" style=\"width: 267px; height: 222px;\" /></p><p>Net force acting on wire&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AB</mi></math>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CD</mi></math>&nbsp;are zero</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9df373a1-3d90-403c-a303-1690aa9cfe00-image.png\" style=\"width: 265px; height: 242px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>L</mi><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>cos&#952;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><msqrt><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>b</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8776;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>&#8810;</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41453,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["outside the cable","inside the outer conductor","inside the inner conductor","in between the two conductors"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rgQ-_l-FCY5tB9Ph7lL-I7zzjn5UpOr3bhcWT35O8LU.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\oint \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{B}} \\cdot \\mathrm{d} \\vec{\\ell}=\\mu_0 \\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{enc}}=0$\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{B}=0$ outside the cable","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41480,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["helical path with the axis perpendicular to the direction of magnetic field <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","helical path with the axis along magnetic field <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","circular path","straight along the direction of magnetic field <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the radius of the path followed by the charged particle under an external magnetic field can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>The perpendicular component of velocity results in circular motion, while the&nbsp;parallel component results in linear motion. Hence, the path of the charged particle is helical in nature, the axis of which lies along the direction of the magnetic field.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41617,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$\\frac{4 N \\mu_0 I}{5^{3 / 2} R}$","$\\frac{8 N \\mu_0 I}{5^{3 / 2} R}$","$\\frac{4 N \\mu_0 I}{5^{1 / 2} R}$","$\\frac{8 N \\mu_0 I}{5^{1 / 2} R}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Point $P$ is situated at the mid-point of the line joining the centres of the circular wires which have same radii (R). The magnetic fields $(\\vec{B})$ at $\\mathrm{P}$ due to the currents in the wires are in same direction.\nMagnitude of magnetic field at point, $P$\n$B=2\\left\\{\\frac{\\mu_0 N I R^2}{2\\left(R^2+\\frac{R^2}{4}\\right)^{3 / 2}}\\right\\}$\n$=\\frac{\\mu_0 N I R^2}{\\frac{5^{3 / 2}}{8}}=\\frac{8 \\mu_0 N I}{5^{3 / 2} R}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":41631,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["(b) and (c), respectively.","(a) and (b), respectively.","(a) and (c), respectively.","(b) and (d), respectively."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>For a magnetic dipole placed in a uniform magnetic field, the torque is given by <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>&#964;</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>, and potential energy <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi></math> is given as,<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>M</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#183;</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math><br /><br />When <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math> is in the same direction as <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math> then <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>&#964;</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi></math> is minimum = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi></math> as <math><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msup></math>.<math><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Stable equilibrium is (b).</p><p>When <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math> the opposite direction of <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>, then <math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>&#964;</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi></math> is max = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi></math><br />As,&nbsp;<math><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>180</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Unstable equilibrium in (d)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41426,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Magnetic field due to $\\mathrm{AB} \\& \\mathrm{CD}=0$<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\mathrm{B}_0=\\left|\\mathrm{B}_{\\mathrm{R}_1}-\\mathrm{B}_{\\mathrm{R}_2}\\right| \\\\\n& =\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{4 \\mathrm{R}_2}-\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{4 \\mathrm{R}_1} \\\\\n& =\\frac{4 \\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 12}{4}\\left(\\frac{1}{4 \\pi}-\\frac{1}{6 \\pi}\\right) \\\\\n& =12 \\pi \\times 10^{-7}\\left(\\frac{1}{12 \\pi}\\right) \\\\\n& =1 \\times 10^{-7}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>$K=1$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41620,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>K</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mi>m</mi></msqrt><mi>q</mi></mfrac></math>. For electron,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfrac><msqrt><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi></msub></msqrt><mi>e</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;Where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;is the mass of an electron.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo></math>the mass of a proton.&nbsp;For alpha particles,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfrac><msqrt><mn>4</mn><mi>m</mi></msqrt><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>e</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfrac><msqrt><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mn></msqrt><mi>e</mi></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo></math>charge on proton. For proton,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>p</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfrac><msqrt><mi>m</mi></msqrt><mi>e</mi></mfrac></math>, so, <math><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#60;</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></msub></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41520,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Magnetic field at the&nbsp;centre of a single coil is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>If&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi></math>&nbsp;number of loops are kept closely&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p>Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>y</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>N</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><msub><mi>N</mi><mi>y</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>y</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41412,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$6 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~N}$ towards $P$","$6 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~N}$ towards $P$","$6 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~N}$ towards $R$","$6 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~N}$ towards $R$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The force per unit length between parallel wires is $F/L = \\frac{\\mu_0 I_1 I_2}{2\\pi d}$.<br>Force on Q from P (opposite currents, repulsive towards R): $\\frac{F_{QP}}{L} = \\frac{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 3 \\times 1}{2\\pi \\times 0.03} = 2 \\times 10^{-5}$ N/m. <br>Force on Q from R (same currents, attractive towards R): $\\frac{F_{QR}}{L} = \\frac{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 1 \\times 2}{2\\pi \\times 0.02} = 2 \\times 10^{-5}$ N/m. <br>Total force per unit length towards R: $4 \\times 10^{-5}$ N/m. <br>For 0.15 m length: $F = 4 \\times 10^{-5} \\times 0.15 = 6 \\times 10^{-6}$ N towards R.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41413,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["4","2","$2 \\sqrt{2}$","8"],"answer":1,"solution":"The magnetic field at the center of a circular loop is $B_{center} = \\frac{\\mu_0 I}{2R} = 16\\mu$ T.<br>On the axis at distance $x$ from center: $B(x) = \\frac{\\mu_0 I R^2}{2(R^2 + x^2)^{3/2}}$.<br>At $x = \\sqrt{3}R$: $B(\\sqrt{3}R) = \\frac{\\mu_0 I R^2}{2(R^2 + 3R^2)^{3/2}} = \\frac{\\mu_0 I R^2}{2(4R^2)^{3/2}} = \\frac{\\mu_0 I}{16R}$.<br>The ratio: $\\frac{B(\\sqrt{3}R)}{B_{center}} = \\frac{1/16R}{1/2R} = \\frac{1}{8}$.<br>Therefore: $B(\\sqrt{3}R) = \\frac{1}{8} \\times 16\\mu = 2\\mu$ T.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41511,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>126</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>312</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>216</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>245</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Force due to magnetic field on a current carrying conductor is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mover><mi>l</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>.</p><p>The angle between the magnetic field and the direction of the current in the wire&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi><mi>D</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>sin</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>216</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41667,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["infinite","zero","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{4 \\pi} \\frac{2 \\mathrm{i}}{r}$ tesla","$2 n^2 \\mathrm{~B}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Considering Ampere's loop (shown by dotted line), no current is enclosed by this loop. Therefore, the magnetic field will be zero inside the tube.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41553,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/89aa1a2e-da03-4636-ae1f-b5f834a1f22d-image.png\" style=\"width: 148px; height: 135px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c6248c3-6e65-4aef-ae23-c059641ccbca-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 142px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4cd21dfe-e124-4048-930c-fb65904f9871-image.png\" style=\"width: 174px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/37a079dd-23bc-4226-b849-ea80904749fb-image.png\" style=\"width: 168px; height: 156px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Graph for wire of radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47100e73-e1e8-47fb-a785-954260377515-image.png\" style=\"width: 226px; height: 171px;\" /></p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>a</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">a</mi></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">b</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">a</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41675,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi r} i_1 i_2 d l \\tan \\theta$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}} \\mathrm{i}_1 \\mathrm{i}_2 \\mathrm{~dl} \\sin \\theta$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}} \\mathrm{i}_1 \\mathrm{i}_2 \\mathrm{dl} \\cos \\theta$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{4 \\pi r} i_1 i_2 d l \\sin \\theta$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":41580,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Pitch</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>Vcos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>Vcos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>)</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mi>eB</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>69</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>19</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41457,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Force on segment parallel to $\\mathrm{x}$-axis will cancel each other. Hence $\\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{net}}$ will be due to portion parallel to $y$-axis.\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& F=0.5 \\times 0.5 \\times 6 \\times 0.2-0.5 \\times 0.5 \\times 0.2 \\times 5 \\\\\n& =0.5 \\times 0.5 \\times 0.2 \\\\\n& =0.25 \\times 0.2 \\\\\n& =50 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~N} \\\\\n& =50 \\mathrm{mN}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41444,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":1,"solution":"Conceptual.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41669,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$250 \\mu \\mathrm{T}$","$150 \\mu \\mathrm{T}$","$125 \\mu \\mathrm{T}$","$75 \\mu \\mathrm{T}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Using formula $B=\\frac{\\mu_0^{\\text {II }}}{2\\left(R^2+X^2\\right)^{3 / 2}}$, we get\n$$\n54=\\frac{\\mu_0 i(3)^2}{2\\left[(3)^2+(4)^2\\right]^{3 / 2}}\n$$\nAt the centre of the coil, $X=0$ and $B=\\frac{\\mu_0 i}{2(3)}$\nUsing equation (i)\n$$\nB=\\frac{54 \\times 5^3}{(3)^2 \\times 3} \\Rightarrow B=250 \\mu \\mathrm{T} \\text {. }\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41537,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Magnetic field due to long solenoid along its axis is given as,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>I</mi></math>,&nbsp;where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;the&nbsp;number of turns in the solenoid per unit length,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math>&nbsp;is current in the solenoid and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a constant called the permeability of free space.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>According to the question,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi></math>; means, the&nbsp;magnetic field remains the same.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41588,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["<math><mn>0.71</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math><mn>7.1</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math><mn>0.071</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math><mn>71</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11cec3bf-16b8-4176-b444-4ba47bc0bd93.jpeg\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1.6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1.6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><math><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mi>m</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>s</mi></math><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi></math><br /><math><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1.6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>0.71</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>T</mi></math><br />So,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>71</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>T</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41660,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi}\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{I}_1+\\mathrm{I}_2}{d}\\right)^{1 / 2}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{d}}\\left(\\mathrm{I}_1^2+\\mathrm{I}_2^2\\right)^{1 / 2}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi d}\\left(\\mathrm{I}_1+\\mathrm{I}_2\\right)$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi d}\\left(\\mathrm{I}_1^2+\\mathrm{I}_2^2\\right)$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{I}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{d}} \\sqrt{\\left(\\mathrm{I}_1^2+\\mathrm{I}_2^2\\right)}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":41636,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["1.57 W","2.97 W","14.85 W","29.7 W"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mtext>Power P</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>W</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>Δ</mtext> <mtext>t</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Force on conductor<br /><math><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>×</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>F</mi> <mo>→</mo> </mover> <mo>=</mo><mn>-10</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>3</mn><msub> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>a</mi> <mo>^</mo> </mover> <mi>z</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>×</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup> <mrow> <mn>10</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <msup> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>0.2</mn><mi>x</mi> </mrow> </msup> <msub> <mover accent=\"true\"> <mi>a</mi> <mo>^</mo> </mover> <mi>y</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0.2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo></math> along with x-axis<br /><br />work done on the conductor in moving along x-axis.<br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><munderover><mo stretchy=\"false\">∫</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></munderover><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>.</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></mover></mrow></mrow></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>W</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <munderover> <mo>∫</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mn>2</mn> </munderover> <mtext>Bi</mtext> <mi>ℓ</mi> <mtext>dx</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <munderover> <mo>∫</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mn>2</mn> </munderover> <mn>3</mn> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>0.2x</mtext> </mrow> </msup> <mo>×</mo> <mn>3</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mtext>10dx</mtext> </mrow> </math><math><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><msubsup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0.2</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0.2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>450</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>[</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>-</mo> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>0.4</mtext> </mrow> </msup> <mo>]</mo> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>180</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mspace width=\"0.5em\"></mspace> <mn>(</mn> <mtext>Using</mtext> <mspace width=\"0.5em\"></mspace> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>x</mtext> </mrow> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>x</mtext> <mn>)</mn> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>P</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>W</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>Δ</mtext> <mtext>t</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>180</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>×</mo> <msup> <mtext>10</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>3.6 W.</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Hence, closest option is 2.97 W.<br />(if we used exact value of exponential term will get exact answer).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41482,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Effects of Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given data is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>60</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></math></p><p>The pitch of the proton is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>By using</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>K</mi></mrow><mi>m</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>Substituting the values in equation (i)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null}]